{
  "Factor: x^2 - 9": "",
  "(x - 9)(x + 1)": "",
  "(x - 3)^2": "",
  "(x - 3)(x + 3)": "",
  "(x + 3)^2": "",
  "This is a difference of squares: a^2 - b^2 = (a-b)(a+b). Here a = x and b = 3, so x^2 - 9 = (x-3)(x+3).": "",
  "Factor completely: 2x^2 + 10x + 12": "",
  "2(x + 6)(x + 1)": "",
  "(x + 2)(2x + 6)": "",
  "2(x + 2)(x + 3)": "",
  "(2x + 4)(x + 3)": "",
  "First factor out the GCF of 2: 2(x^2 + 5x + 6). Then factor the trinomial: 2(x + 2)(x + 3).": "",
  "Factor: x^3 - 8": "",
  "(x - 2)(x^2 + 2x + 4)": "",
  "(x - 2)(x^2 - 2x + 4)": "",
  "(x - 2)^3": "",
  "(x + 2)(x^2 - 2x + 4)": "",
  "This is a difference of cubes: a^3 - b^3 = (a - b)(a^2 + ab + b^2). With a = x and b = 2: (x - 2)(x^2 + 2x + 4).": "",
  "Factor: x^3 + 27": "",
  "(x + 3)^3": "",
  "(x + 3)(x^2 + 3x + 9)": "",
  "(x + 3)(x^2 - 3x + 9)": "",
  "(x - 3)(x^2 + 3x + 9)": "",
  "Sum of cubes: a^3 + b^3 = (a + b)(a^2 - ab + b^2). With a = x and b = 3: (x + 3)(x^2 - 3x + 9).": "",
  "Factor by grouping: x^3 + 2x^2 + 3x + 6": "",
  "(x^2 + 3)(x + 2)": "",
  "x(x^2 + 2x + 3) + 6": "",
  "(x^2 + 2)(x + 3)": "",
  "(x + 1)(x^2 + 6)": "",
  "Group: x^2(x + 2) + 3(x + 2) = (x^2 + 3)(x + 2). The common factor (x + 2) is extracted from both groups.": "",
  "Factor: 6x^2 + 7x - 3": "",
  "(3x - 1)(2x + 3)": "",
  "(6x - 1)(x + 3)": "",
  "(2x - 1)(3x + 3)": "",
  "(3x + 1)(2x - 3)": "",
  "We need factors of 6*(-3) = -18 that add to 7: 9 and -2. Rewrite: 6x^2 + 9x - 2x - 3 = 3x(2x + 3) - 1(2x + 3) = (3x - 1)(2x + 3).": "",
  "Factor completely: x^4 - 16": "",
  "(x^2 + 4)(x + 2)(x - 2)": "",
  "(x - 2)^2(x + 2)^2": "",
  "(x^2 - 4)(x^2 + 4)": "",
  "(x^2 + 4)(x^2 - 4)": "",
  "First use difference of squares: (x^2 - 4)(x^2 + 4). Then factor x^2 - 4 again: (x - 2)(x + 2)(x^2 + 4). Note x^2 + 4 cannot be factored over the reals.": "",
  "Factor: 3x^3 - 12x": "",
  "3x(x^2 - 4)": "",
  "x(3x^2 - 12)": "",
  "3(x^3 - 4x)": "",
  "3x(x - 2)(x + 2)": "",
  "Factor out GCF: 3x(x^2 - 4). Then apply difference of squares: 3x(x - 2)(x + 2). Always factor completely.": "",
  "Factor: x^2 - 7x + 12": "",
  "(x - 2)(x - 6)": "",
  "(x - 1)(x - 12)": "",
  "(x - 3)(x - 4)": "",
  "(x + 3)(x + 4)": "",
  "Find two numbers that multiply to 12 and add to -7: -3 and -4. So x^2 - 7x + 12 = (x - 3)(x - 4).": "",
  "Factor: 8x^3 + 1": "",
  "(2x + 1)(4x^2 + 2x + 1)": "",
  "(2x + 1)^3": "",
  "(8x + 1)(x^2 + 1)": "",
  "(2x + 1)(4x^2 - 2x + 1)": "",
  "Sum of cubes: (2x)^3 + 1^3 = (2x + 1)((2x)^2 - (2x)(1) + 1^2) = (2x + 1)(4x^2 - 2x + 1).": "",
  "What does it mean to 'factor' a polynomial?": "",
  "To find the value of x": "",
  "To simplify by combining like terms": "",
  "To write it as a product of simpler polynomial expressions": "",
  "To divide by the highest power": "",
  "Factoring a polynomial means expressing it as a product of two or more simpler polynomials. It is the reverse of multiplication (expanding).": "",
  "What is the 'Greatest Common Factor' (GCF) in factoring?": "",
  "The largest coefficient in the polynomial": "",
  "The product of all coefficients": "",
  "The highest-degree term": "",
  "The largest expression that divides evenly into all terms of the polynomial": "",
  "The GCF is the largest factor (including both numerical and variable parts) that is common to every term in the polynomial. It should always be factored out first.": "",
  "What is a 'difference of squares'?": "",
  "Any expression with two squared terms": "",
  "An expression of the form a^2 - b^2 that factors as (a - b)(a + b)": "",
  "An expression of the form a^2 + b^2": "",
  "The result of subtracting two numbers": "",
  "A difference of squares is a^2 - b^2, which always factors as (a - b)(a + b). Note that a sum of squares a^2 + b^2 cannot be factored over the real numbers.": "",
  "What is the 'sum of cubes' formula?": "",
  "a^3 + b^3 = (a + b)(a^2 - ab + b^2)": "",
  "a^3 + b^3 = (a + b)^3": "",
  "a^3 + b^3 = (a + b)(a^2 + ab + b^2)": "",
  "a^3 + b^3 = (a - b)(a^2 + ab + b^2)": "",
  "The sum of cubes formula is a^3 + b^3 = (a + b)(a^2 - ab + b^2). Notice the signs follow the pattern: Same, Opposite, Always Positive (SOAP).": "",
  "What is the 'difference of cubes' formula?": "",
  "a^3 - b^3 = (a + b)(a^2 - ab + b^2)": "",
  "a^3 - b^3 = (a - b)^3": "",
  "a^3 - b^3 = (a - b)(a^2 + ab + b^2)": "",
  "a^3 - b^3 = (a - b)(a^2 - ab + b^2)": "",
  "The difference of cubes formula is a^3 - b^3 = (a - b)(a^2 + ab + b^2). The first factor matches the sign, the middle term of the trinomial is opposite.": "",
  "What does 'factoring by grouping' mean?": "",
  "Dividing the polynomial into equal groups in most standard conditions": "",
  "Factoring out the GCF only, particularly regarding mean under the given assumptions": "",
  "Grouping all like terms together when applying fundamental principles": "",
  "Grouping terms in pairs to find common factors within each group, then factoring out the shared binomial": "",
  "Factoring by grouping pairs terms and factors out a common expression from each group. If both groups share a common binomial factor, it can be factored out to complete the factorization.": "",
  "What does 'irreducible' mean for a polynomial factor?": "",
  "A polynomial with only one term": "",
  "A polynomial equal to zero": "",
  "A polynomial that cannot be factored further over the given number system": "",
  "A polynomial with no real coefficients": "",
  "An irreducible (or prime) polynomial cannot be factored into polynomials of lower degree using coefficients from the given number system. For example, x^2 + 1 is irreducible over the reals.": "",
  "What is 'factoring completely'?": "",
  "Factoring out only the GCF": "",
  "Writing the polynomial in standard form": "",
  "Breaking a polynomial into the product of irreducible factors and any GCF": "",
  "Finding one pair of factors": "",
  "Factoring completely means expressing the polynomial as a product of its GCF and irreducible polynomial factors. No factor should be factorable further.": "",
  "What is a 'zero' of a polynomial in relation to factoring?": "",
  "A value of x that makes a factor (and thus the polynomial) equal to zero": "",
  "The constant term of the polynomial": "",
  "The degree of the polynomial": "",
  "A coefficient that equals zero": "",
  "A zero of a polynomial is an x-value where f(x) = 0. By the zero product property, if a polynomial is in factored form, setting each factor equal to zero gives the zeros.": "",
  "What is the 'zero product property'?": "",
  "A polynomial always has at least one zero": "",
  "If the product of factors equals zero, then at least one factor must equal zero": "",
  "Multiplying any number by zero gives zero": "",
  "Zero divided by any number is zero": "",
  "The zero product property states that if ab = 0, then a = 0 or b = 0. This principle is fundamental to solving polynomial equations by factoring.": "",
  "A box manufacturer cuts squares of side x from corners of a 20 by 14 inch sheet to make an open box. The volume is V = x(20-2x)(14-2x). If the volume equals zero, what are the possible values of x?": "",
  "x = 0, x = 7, or x = 10": "",
  "x = 7 or x = 10": "",
  "x = 0 only": "",
  "x = 0, x = 14, or x = 20": "",
  "Setting V = 0: x(20-2x)(14-2x) = 0. By zero product property: x = 0, 20-2x = 0 (x = 10), or 14-2x = 0 (x = 7).": "",
  "A ball's height is h(t) = -16t^2 + 48t. By factoring, find when it hits the ground.": "",
